[2] Brazil (Rio de Janeiro)
Date: Tue 11 Aug 2009
Source: eBand [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.band.com.br/jornalismo/cidades/conteudo.asp?ID=164506>


In the capital, cases rose 50 percent in the 1st half of 2009, from
214 to 322. According Bronislaw de Castro, coordinator of dengue
surveillance in the municipality, the increase is not representative.
In 2009 [incidence] was 2.9 cases per 100 000 inhabitants. The
Ministry of Health considers the transmission to be low up to 100
cases [per 100 000]. "Even in 2007, the incidence was 24.2 per 100
000. To have an epidemic in the city, it would take 33 000 cases in
the year," he said.

[Byline: Gabriel Attuy]

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The article also mentioned that dengue virus types 1, 2, and 3 have
circulated previously in the city, and that a major concern was the
appearance of dengue virus type 4 there, for which there would be no
immunity. Mod.-TY]

[Rio de Janeiro can be located on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail
interactive map of Brazil at <http://healthmap.org/r/00GS>. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]

******
[3] El Salvador
Date: Sat 15 Aug 2009
Source: Xinhua News Agency [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2009-08/15/content_11886307.htm>


El Salvador's Health Ministry designated 26 Aug [2009] as its
national anti-dengue day since the number of confirmed dengue cases
has topped to 1145, up 36 percent year-on-year, according to news
reaching [Mexico City] on Friday [14 Aug 2009].

"We have made several plans to tackle dengue and flu. But the most
important one is to avoid mosquito breeding," said health minister
Eduardo Espinoza. Dengue fever is [caused by] a mosquito-borne
tropical virus that causes muscle pain, internal bleeding, and death.
The rainy season (May to October) increases the amount of stagnant
water, a breeding ground for dengue [virus]-carrying _Aedes_
mosquitoes, thus increasing the spread of dengue and flu. [_Aedes_
mosquitoes are not involved in the transmission of flu (influenza)
virus. - Mod.TY]

[Byline: Xiong Tong, editor]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Brent Barrett

