[4] Guatemala
Date: Sun 16 Aug 2009
Source: Latin American Herald Tribune, Agencia EFE report [edited]
<http://www.laht.com/article.asp?ArticleId=341208&CategoryId=23558>


Guatemalan health officials on Tuesday [11 Aug 2009] confirmed that 2
people have died from DHF in the Caribbean province of Izabal, where
there were reports that at least 8 children died from the disease in
the past few weeks. An investigation conducted last week confirmed
that at least 2 people died from the disease in the region, the
Health Ministry said.

Dengue is a serious viral disease transmitted by the _Aedes aegypti_
mosquito that is characterized by high fever, intense headaches,
muscle pain, gastro-intestinal problems, and rashes. DHF, in addition
to having symptoms associated with classic dengue, like fever,
headaches, and joint pain, can also produce internal bleeding.

Opposition GANA [Grand National Alliance] party Congressman Byron
Chacon, who represents Izabal, said last Thursday [13 Aug 2009] that
8 children had died from DHF and 69 other people were infected with
the disease in his district. Health Minister Celso Cerezo said,
however, that 2 people had died and 16 others had been infected with
DHF, but they were all recovering.

A total of 115 cases of classic dengue have also been detected in
Izabal, health officials said. Dengue is common in Izabal, which does
not have drains, allowing the mosquitoes that spread the disease
[virus] to breed in standing water.

--
Communicated by
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Brent Barrett

